---
import TopNav from "../components/TopNav.astro";
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" href="/NH%20DB%20Logo.png" />
    <link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/NH%20DB%20Logo.png" />
    <title>How Vote Grades Work | NH Deserves Better</title>
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="How NH Deserves Better calculates legislator vote grades from tracked bills, public testimony, and documented votes."
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <TopNav />
    <main class="page">
      <a class="back" href="/">Back home</a>

      <section class="hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Methodology</p>
        <h1>How Vote Grades Work</h1>
        <p>
          Vote grades are meant to be a plain-language accountability signal,
          not the whole story. They help visitors quickly understand how often a
          legislator's recorded votes line up with the public-interest position
          we can determine from the bill tracker and public testimony.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="panel">
        <h2>The Basic Idea</h2>
        <p>
          Legislators start from a middle baseline. Recorded votes can move the
          grade up or down depending on whether they align with the preferred
          stance for a bill. Missed or documented non-votes receive partial
          credit rather than being treated the same as a clearly aligned vote.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="grid">
        <article class="panel">
          <h2>What We Score</h2>
          <p>
            Grades use voting actions with documented vote data. When a bill is
            in our tracker, the tracker can provide the preferred stance and the
            interpretation of yea and nay votes.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="panel">
          <h2>Public Testimony</h2>
          <p>
            When a tracker stance is not available, public testimony can help
            infer the community position. Support and opposition counts are used
            as context, especially on vote cards and roll-call views.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="panel">
          <h2>Non-Votes</h2>
          <p>
            If a legislator is absent, present but not voting, or otherwise has
            a documented non-vote, the grade reflects that as partial
            accountability. Missing a vote matters, but it is displayed
            differently from voting against the preferred stance.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="panel">
          <h2>Letter Scale</h2>
          <p>
            The percentage score is converted into a familiar letter grade:
            higher alignment produces A or B grades, middle scores produce C or
            D grades, and low alignment produces an F.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section class="panel note">
        <h2>Why This Matters</h2>
        <p>
          New Hampshire has a very large legislature. A simple grade helps make
          patterns easier to see, but it should be read alongside the underlying
          bill summaries, vote explanations, testimony, and roll-call records.
        </p>
        <a href="/vote-interpretations">How vote labels work</a>
      </section>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>

<style>
  :global(body) {
    margin: 0;
    font-family:
      Inter, ui-sans-serif, system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI",
      sans-serif;
    background: #f7f4ee;
    color: #1f2933;
  }

  .page {
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 40px 0 72px;
    width: min(1040px, calc(100% - 32px));
  }

  .back,
  a {
    color: #1f2933;
    font-weight: 900;
  }

  .hero {
    padding: 28px 0 18px;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    color: #6b4f2a;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 950;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    margin: 0 0 10px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.45rem, 7vw, 4.8rem);
    line-height: 0.95;
    margin: 0 0 18px;
  }

  h2 {
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    margin: 0 0 10px;
  }

  p {
    color: #4b5563;
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .hero p {
    font-size: 1.08rem;
    max-width: 760px;
  }

  .grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: 16px;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    margin-top: 16px;
  }

  .panel {
    background: white;
    border: 2px solid #1f2933;
    border-radius: 8px;
    box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 #1f2933;
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .note {
    margin-top: 16px;
  }

  .note a {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: 14px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
